Title:
ROFMAD (Rust Orchestrator For Modular Automated Discovery)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
ROFMAD is a Rust-based orchestration framework for automated internal network reconnaissance and enumeration, built to run primarily inside Exegol containers on Linux. It automates a multi-stage pipeline (host discovery → full TCP port scan → targeted service/version scan → HTTP probing → tagging → screenshots) and persists state in SQLite so projects can be resumed. The core extensibility is a YAML workflow engine that triggers operator-defined actions based on conditions (ports/services/tags/HTTP presence) and applies tags via regex matches on tool output, without embedding “AI” decision-making. It integrates common tooling (nmap, masscan, arp-scan, tcpdump, nuclei, headless Chromium) and provides a real-time web UI for queue monitoring, concurrency controls, and per-host drilldowns. Safety features include interface/localhost protection and configurable IP/CIDR blacklisting enforced across scanners. It’s useful for red teams and pentesters who want repeatable, scalable enumeration workflows with visibility and task control.

Technical Focus:
- Event/hook-driven scan orchestration with deduplication and polling loop
- YAML-defined conditional workflows and placeholder substitution (e.g., `{{IP}}`, `{{HTTP_URL}}`)
- Multi-phase subnet scanning strategy (masscan funnel + staged nmap coverage)
- HTTP service fingerprinting and automated screenshotting (headless Chrome)
- Nuclei integration (per-service and bulk) with severity dashboards
- SQLite-backed project state, tagging system, and resumable runs

Use Cases:
- Automate internal network discovery and enumeration during authorized pentests
- Build repeatable recon playbooks (SMB/MSSQL/HTTP) via YAML actions without code changes
- Run bulk Nuclei scans scoped by tags/IP ranges and triage findings in a UI
- Coordinate multi-operator (“player”) recon with shared project state and role separation
- Export tagged target sets (TXT/CSV/JSON) for follow-on exploitation or reporting

Keywords:
Rust, Tokio, Axum, Askama, SQLite, sqlx, Exegol, nmap, masscan, arp-scan, tcpdump, nuclei, headless Chromium, HTTP probing, service enumeration, YAML workflow, regex tagging, concurrency semaphores, blacklisting, internal network reconnaissance